column168: DRIVER WAS SOUTHBOUND ON HWY 40 NEAR EMPIRE.  HE WAS TRAVELING EMPTY.  HE THOUGHT THE BRAKES FELT SPONGY AND WHAT HE FELT MIGHT BE AN AIR LEAK, SO HE PULLED THE TRUCK OVER, STOPPED AND PUT ON HIS BRAKES, GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK, BENT DOWN TO LOOK UNDER THE TRUCK, THE TRUCK STARTED ROLLING AWAY. THE VEHICLE TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 15 TO 20 FT. OVER AN EMBANKMENT.  AT 1:45 P.M. MT, IDAHO SPRINGS GEORGETOWN & DUMONT FIRE DEPT. EVACUATED THE TRAILER PARK THAT WAS WITH 300 FT. TANK EMPTY BUT IT HAD NOT BEEN PURGED. SOME RESIDUAL VAPOR WAS STILL IN TANK.  AT 2:00 P.M. MT US 40 WAS CLOSED TO THRU TRAFFIC.  IT WAS CLOSED UNTIL 2:45 P.M. MT. RESIDENTS OF THE MOBILE HOME PARK WERE ALLOWED TO RETURNED TO THEIR HOMES AT THAT TIME.

I NEUTRALIZED THE ODOR WITH ACTIVATED CARBON AND ABSORBED ALL EXCESS LIQUID WITH CLAY ABSORBENT.  I THEN DISPOSED OF ALL CONTAMINATED WASTE VIA DMP PROGRAM.  I THEN DECONTAMINATED MY PPE.

column168: AT 23:30 ON 4-4-99, A ROLL-OFF BOX IN A 10-DAY TRANSFER FACILITY WAS DISCOVERED TO BE ON FIRE.  THE CALUMET CITY, IL., FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE.   THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST AND WASTE PROFILE SHEET WERE REVIEWED AND THE WASTE WAS IDENTIFIED AS A BAGHOUSE DUST FROM THE FIRE AIR HANDLING SYSTEM OFF OF A FURNACE IN THE SMELT OF ALUMINUM.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE USING A FOAM AND DIRT PLACED ON THE FIRE.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS WATER, FOAM DIRT AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF WASTE WHICH OVERFILLED THE ROLL-OFF WHILE EXTINGUISHING THE FIRE.  THE WASTE WAS ORIGINALLY RQ'ED FOR THE MADE, KNOWING THE LEVELS OF CADMIUM AND LEAD IN THE WASTE, TO DETERMINE IF AN RQ RELEASE HAD OCCURRED.  THE CALCULATIONS DETERMINED THAT THE WASTE IN THE CONTAINER DID NOT CONTAIN RQ LEVELS OF CADMIUM OR LEAD.  THE GENERATOR BELIEVES THE FIRE OCCURRED BECAUSE VIRGIN ALUMINUM DUST AND IRON OXIDES AND MISTAKENLY BEEN ADDED TO THE WASTE.  A.E.B., HAS REFUSED TO HANDLE ANY ADDITIONAL WASTE FROM THE GENERATOR UNTIL HE CAN ASSURE US THAT THE INCIDENT WILL NOT RECUR.

column168: A FUEL ODOR WAS COMING FROM THIS PACKAGE DURING THE INBOUND FREIGHT SORT OPERATIONS IN SEATTLE.  WHEN THE BOX WAS OPENED BY A FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST, THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR WAS FOUND TO BE SOME FUEL THAT HAD LEAKED OUT A SMALL FUEL TANK THAT WAS ON A ENGINE CONNECTED TO A PUMP.  THE DEVICE WAS WRAPPED IN PLASTIC, BUT THE CAP ON THE FUEL TANK HAD BECOME LOOSE AND ABOUT 120 ML OF FUEL HAD LEAKED OUT.  THIS SHIPMENT HAD NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELINGS ON THE OUTER BOX AND THERE WAS NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PAPERWORK OFFERED TO UPON AND INVESTIGATED THIS INCIDENT ON THE SAME DAY IT WAS REPORTED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RELEASE AFTER THE INVESTIGATION AND WAS PICKED UP BY THE RECIPIENT AT THE FEDEX FACILITY.
THE DRUM WAS NOT OBSERVED BEING DAMAGED BUT WHEN NOTICED SITTING ON THE CONCRETE IT WAS LEAKING AROUND THE SEAM/WELD AND APPEARED TO BE DENTED AS IF HIT OR DROPPED.

THE PACKAGE HAD FELL ON THE RAMP AND WAS RAN OVER BY A LOADER WHOSE DRIVER DIDN'T SEE IT.  THE DRUM AND PACKAGE WERE CRUSHED AND NOT ALL INFORMATION WAS OBTAINABLE.  SHIPPER NOTIFIED AND PACKAGE DISPOSED OF LOCALLY.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD, BECAUSE THE OUTER BOX HAD BEEN SOAKED BY A MATERIAL THAT SMELLED LIKE A FLAMMABLE SOLVENT.  THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED DURING THE INBOUND SORT OPERATIONS.  SINCE IT WAS BELIEVED THAT THIS INNER PLASTIC DRUM HAD LEAKED, THE SPILL SPECIALIST REQUESTED THE MSDS FROM THE SHIPPER.  I WAS CALLED ABOUT THIS UNDECLARED PACKAGE, BUT THE MSDS WAS DELAYED IN BEING SENT TO ME, BECAUSE IT WAS COMING FROM THE MANUFACTURER.  UPON REVIEW OF THE MSDS, I CONTACTED THE FAA ABOUT THIS UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. THIS PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS AND THERE WAS NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK OFFERED TO FEDEX UPON PACKAGE ACCEPTANCE.  THIS BOX IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

WE IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF ALL IGNITION SOURCES, KEPT OTHER FORKLIFT AWAY FROM THE AREA. WE THEN PUT ABSORB ALL ON THE LIQUID INSIDE THE TRAILER, AND AT THE SAME TIME WE LAID THE DRUMS ON THEIR SIDES TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE. WE THEN CLEANED UP ALL LIQUID AND PLACED THE CONTAMINATED ABSORB ALL IN DRUMS AND THREW THEM AWAY. WE THEN PLACED BOTH 53 GAL. DRUMS INTO SEPARATE OVER PACKS, LABELED THEM AND THEN PLACED THEM IN OUR HAZ MAT STORAGE AREA. I SPOKE WITH THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR AND TOLD HIM IF AT ANY TIME HE SEES LIQUID ON THE DOCK PLATE STOP IMMEDIATELY AND GET THE SPILLED LIQUID CLEANED UP BEFORE PROCEEDING INTO THE TRAILER.

column168: DRIVER DEPARTED SHIPPER LOCATION 4/1 WITH A LOAD OF 46820 POUNDS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE, 50%.  AT DESTINATION 4/1, .3 MI AFTER CONSIGNEE WEIGHT SCALE AT CONSIGNEE LAB INSIDE CONSIGNEE PLANT, DRIVER NOTICED THAT A "FEW DRIPS" OF PRODUCT WERE VISIBLE COMING FROM THE HOSE ATTACHED TO THE AIR BLEED-OFF VALVE ON THE TANK TRAILER:  "NOT A PUDDLE.  DRIVER LOOKED BEHIND HIM, SAW NO PRODUCT ON THE GROUND/STREET OR ELSEWHERE.  HOWEVER THE AIR BLEED-OFF VALVE WAS PARTIALLY OPEN.  THE DRIVER COMPLETED CLOSURE OF THE AIR VALVE, COMPLETED DELIVERY.  THE CONSIGNEE REPORTED THE SHIPPER ON APRIL 13 THAT PRODUCT WAS FOUND BY THE CONSIGNEE ON 4/1 ON THE GROUND WITHIN THE CONSIGNEE PLANT ON THE STREET BETWEEN THE WEIGHT SCALE AND THE LAB WHERE THE AIR VALVE WAS CLOSED.  THIS AMOUNT WAS ESTIMATED BY THE CONSIGNEE TO BE TWENTY GALLONS.  INVESTIGATION REVEALS THAT NET WEIGHT ON DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER ON 4/1 WAS 46820 AND AT THE CONSIGNEE WEIGHT SCALE 4/1 WAS 46760.  HUBOMETER DISTANCE WAS 4 MILES FROM SCALE TO SCALE.  THE DIFFERENCE WAS 60 POUNDS, FUEL WAS ONE GALLON @ 7# PER GALLON, LADING WEIGHT 13# PER GALLON FOR A DIFFERENCE OF ABOUT FOUR GALLONS COULD BE LOST ON THE STREET FROM SHIPPER TO CONSIGNEE.  AN INSPECTION OF THE ROUTE DID NOT REVEAL ANY EVIDENCE OF SUCH LOSS, BUT TIME ELAPSED WOULD BE A FACTOR.  SINCE DISTANCE FROM WEIGHT SCALE INSIDE CONSIGNEE TO THE LAB WHERE VALVE WAS CLOSED WAS .3 MI IT SEEMS UNLIKELY THAT 20 GALLONS WERE LOST IN CONSIGNEE FACILITY.  ALL VALVES ON THIS TRAILER WERE AREA PRESSURE TESTED ON APRIL 14 TO 50# AND FOUND TO BE WITHOUT LEAKS:  1) CAUSTIC LOADING PROCEDURES REVIEWED.  THEY CONTAIN SPECIFIC INSTRUCTION TO CLOSING AIR BLEED-OFF AND AIR PRESSURE VALVES, AND AN ADDITIONAL SPECIFIC INSTRUCTION TO INSPECT AND VERIFY THAT ALL AIR VALVES ARE CLOSED.  CHANGE: FORM BEING CHANGED TO INCLUDE A CHECK-OFF FORM WHICH LISTS ITEMS FOR CHECK-OFF BEFORE DEPARTURE, AND A SHIPPER SIGN-OFF WILL BE REQUIRED BEFORE TRUCK CAN LEAVE.  2) EXISTING TRAINING, WHICH SPECIFIES THAT ALL SPILLS OF ANY KIND ARE CLASSIFIED AS EMERGENCIES AT VERTEX CHEMICAL AND TO BE REPORTED IMMEDIATELY, HAS BEEN REPEATED IN PERSON BY PLANT MANAGER WITH ALL DRIVERS/CONTRACTORS.  3)  VERTEX GAVE STEVE'S TRUCKING COUNSELING, WRITTEN WARNING THAT FUTURE INCIDENTS WILL DISQUALIFY THEM AS A CONTRACTOR TO VERTEX.  4)  STEVE'S TRUCKING HAS GIVEN DRIVER COUNSELING, AND WRITTEN WARNING THAT FUTURE INCIDENTS WILL DISQUALIFY HIM AS A CONTRACTOR TO STEVE'S TRUCKING.

column168: On April 24, 1999, at approximately 1930 hours, a railroad tank car number GATX 92859, loaded with Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S., Trade Name Calumet Lantern Fuel, was observed leaking from the dome lid while being switched at KCS' Shreveport, Louisiana rail yard.The leaking tank car was immediately isolated and the shipper (responsible party) was notified.  It was determined that the tank car was overfilled, causing a small amount of product to release from the dome lid seal.  The product released to the outer shell of the tank car, where it rapidly evaporated, with no product contacting the ground.  The shipper representative responded to the scene at 2140 hours, on 4/24/99, and made arrangements for off-loading the tank car to attain appropriate outage.

The band on one of the lids was loose and allowed produce to leak onto the trailer floor.  By the time our driver arrived a the consignee the 3 or 4 cups of product that had spilled had already absorbed into the trailer floor.  This shipment was accepted by the consignee and our trailer was swept out.  Next our driver washed the trailer to clean out any remaining residue that might have existed, before he continued on.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE DRIVER, ERNEST GUITERREZ, LOST CONTROL OF GASOLINE BOBTAIL, WHILE NEGOTIATING A CURVE, GOING DOWN THE STEEP CANADIAN RIVER CANYON WEST OF ROY, NM.  THE TRUCK WENT INTO A SKID.  THE DRIVER OVER-CORRECTED AND THE VEHICLE OVERTURNED, THROWING OUT THE DRIVER, KILLING HIM INSTANTLY.  THE HATCH ON COMPARTMENT #1, WHICH CONTAINED 500 GLAS. OF UNLEADED GASOLINE, WAS RIPPED OPEN, CAUSING SOME OF THE GASOLINE TO SPILL, AS THE TRUCK CONTINUED TO ROLL DOWN THE CANYON. THE TRUCK THEN JUMPED THE GUARD RAIL AND CONTINUED ANOTHER 150' COMING TO A REST ON ITS WHEELS.  THE TRUCK IGNITED AND BURNED FOR SEVERAL HOURS.  ALL OF THE FUEL WAS IGNIGTED ALSO AND BURNED UNTIL THE FUEL WAS EXHAUSTED.  NO OTHER FUEL WAS SPILLED OUT OF THE COMPARTMENT SINCE THE VEHICLE WAS RIGHT SIDE UP; HOWEVER, THE REMAINING GASOLINE IN THE COMPARTMENT CONTINUED TO FUEL THE TRUCK FIRE.  NONE OF THE OTHER THREE COMPARTMENTS CONTAINED ANY PRODUCT.

UPON ARRIVING AT THE CUSTOMER LOCATION, THE LOCKHART CONCRETE FOREMAN STUCK THE TANK AT 17" WHICH THE BP DRIVER VERIFIED.  THE FOREMAN ENSURED THE DRIVER THE LOAD WOULD FIT.  THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO PUMP THE LOAD INTO THE TANK WHILE THE JOB SITE FOREMAN STOOD ON TOP OF THE TANK TO PREVENT OVERFILLING.  AS THE TANK STARTED TO FILL, THE FOREMAN MISJUDGED THE FILL RATE,AND THE DRIVER STOPPED PUMPING THE LOAD TOO LATE, CAUSING THE 15 GALLON SPILL.  TO PREVENT FURTHER OCCURRENCES THE TANK WAS MEASURED AND AN ACCURATE TANK CHART WAS CREATED.  IN THE FUTURE THE TANK CHART WILL BE USED TO VERIFY THAT ANY FUTURE LOADS WILL PROPERLY FIT INTO THE TANK.

A warehouseman inspecting drums in temporary storage found a 55-gallon drum with a pin hole leak.  Approximately one gallon of waste had leaked into secondary containment.  The warehouseman overpacked the leaking drum and absorbed the spilled material.  This spillage created ten pounds of waste that was transported, along with the original waste, to the Safety-Kleen facility at 3700 Lagrange Road, Smithfield, KY for treatment/disposal. The warehouseman was counseled to inspect all incoming drums for pin hole leaks.

A driver preparing to unload his vehicle noticed that a 55 gallon drum had leaked about 30 gallons of waste into the secondary containment of his truck.  The drum leaked due to a damaged chime on the bottom of the drum.  The driver overpacked the drum and absorbed on the spilled material.  This spill created 300 pounds of waste that was treated/disposed of at the Safety-Kleen facility 1722 Cooper Creek Road Denton TX.  the driver was counseled to inspect drums for damaged or leaking chimes prior to loading them on his truck.

A driver inspecting his load prior to unloading found a 5-gallon fiber drum with a cut caused by other cargo when the drum shifted during transport.  Approximately four gallons of waste had leaked into secondary containment of the truck.  The driver transferred the contents of the leaking drum into another fiber drum and absorbed the spilled material.  This spill created forty pounds of waste that was transported, along with the original waste, to the Safety-Kleen facility at 581 Milliken Dr SE, Hebron OH for treatment/disposal. The driver was counseled to ensure loads are properly secured to avoid shifting during transport.

A driver loading waste into a cargo tank overfilled the tank allowing 12 gallons of waste to spill into secondary containment. The spilled material on the tank and in secondary containment was absorbed and recovered into drums for later processing.  This spill generated 120 pounds of waste that was transported, along with the original waste, to the Safety-Kleen facility at 1640 Antioch Pike, Antioch, TN for treatment/disposal.  The driver was counseled to use closely attend his tanker to avoid future overfill situations.

A driver unloading drums into a dump and fill tank noticed a stinger was not attached to the bottom of the tank and waste was spilling into the secondary containment below the tank.  As a result forty eight gallons of waste spilled.  The driver attached a stinger to the tank and pumped the spilled material from the sump back into the truck for processing.  This waste was eventually consolidated with other waste and sent on for treatment/disposal at the Safety-Kleen facility at 1722 Cooper Creek Road, Denton TX.  The driver was briefed to ensure fittings are attached prior to unloading drums into other tanks.

A driver unloading drums into a dump and fill tank noticed a stinger was not attached to the bottom of the tank and waste was spilling into the secondary containment below the tank. column168: THERE WAS AN AMMONIA TYPE OF SMELL DISCOVERED AT THE FEDEX  MIAA STATION DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT OPERATION.  THIS PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE THE SOURCE PACKAGE ACCORDING TO THE SPILL CLEAN-UP SPECIALIST.  I WAS CALLED ABOUT THIS ODOR AND POSSIBLE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT AFTER THE PACKAGE WAS MOVED TO AN OPEN AREA OF THE FEDEX FACILITY.  THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MARKINGS OR LABELING ON THE BOX AND NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS OFFERED TO US.  WHEN THE BOX WAS OPENED BY THE SPILL CLEAN-UP SPECIALIST IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN SOME TYPE OF COOLING UNIT THAT CONTAINED 28% AMMONIA (ACCORDING TO THE MSDS SHEET FROM THE MANUFACTURER).  THE FAA WAS CALLED ABOUT THIS POSSIBLE UNDECLARED AND UPON THEIR INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THIS FALLS UNDER ICAO A26 FOR A REFRIGERATING MACHINE THAT CONTAINS LESS THAN 12 LITERS OF AMMONIA SOLUTION (UN 2672) AND THERE FORE DECIDED NOT TO PURSUE A HIDDEN SHIPMENT CASE ON THIS SHIPMENT.  FAA AGENT KEVIN FITZPATRICK WORKED ON THIS CASE.

column168: FOUND BAG LEAKING DUE TO ANOTHER PALLET HITTING BAG AND TEARING BAG ON END.  PUTTING DUNNAGE AROUND BAGS WOULD PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING.

DURING THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING TRAILER, IT WAS NOTICED THAT ONE OF THE BOXES OF MATERIAL WAS LEAKING.  AFTER OPENING THE BOX, IT WAS FOUND THAT TONE OF THE INNER PACKAGINGS HAD BEEN CRUSHED AND SPILLAGE HAD OCCURRED FORM IT.

THIS WAS AN INTER MODAL SHIPMENT THAT ORIGINATED IN JAPAN.  WE PICKED UP THE CONTAINER AT THE CSX RAILROAD IN BEDFORD PARK, IL., AND DELIVERED TO GREEN BAY, WI.  THE CONTAINER WAS BACKED INTO THE DOCK FOR UNLOADING.  THE DRIVER WAS INTO HE CAB OF HIS TRACTOR. DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS, IT WAS DISCOVERED BY THE FORK LIFT OPERATOR THAT THE LOAD HAD SOMEHOW SHIFTED OVER TO ONE SIDE AND A PALLET RUBBED THE SIDE OF TOW BAGS CAUSING THEM TO PUNCTURE OPEN. APPROXIMATELY, 50 POUNDS OF THE MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE CONTAINER FLOOR.  GEN CORP(THE CONSIGNEE) IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED MISUBISHI (THE SHIPPER) TO ADVISE THEM OF THE SPILL.  THEY CONTACTED A RECOVERY TEAM TO PICK-UP THE DAMAGED BAGS AND SPILLED PRODUCT AND RETURN IT TO JAPAN.  PER CONVERSATION WIT MITSUBISHI, THEY ARE GOING TO TAKE ONE OF THE FOLLOWING ADDITIONAL BLOCKING PROCEDURES TO AVOID ANY FUTURE PROBLEMS:  1.  PROTECT THE BAGS WITH A SHEET OF PLYWOOD IN BETWEEN EACH LAYER OF BAGS ON THE PALLETS, OR 2.  PLACING A PIECE OF PLYWOOD VERTICALLY IN BETWEEN THE PALLETS TO PROTECT THE BAGS FROM TH PALLETS RUBBING UP AGAINST THEM INCASE OF THE LOAD SHIFTING.  I WAS UNABLE TO OBTAIN INFORMATION FOR #34, 35, 36 ABOVE.  I WILL FORWARD AS SOON AS IN RECEIVE IT.

THIS SHIPMENT CAME IN ONE TRAILER AND WAS RELOADED ON ANOTHER.  IT WAS OBSERVED THAT GAS WAS LEAKING FROM THE STEEL CANISTER.  THE PRO # AND SHIPPING PAPERS WERE OBTAINED AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE CANISTER HAD GOTTEN TO THE POINT THAT THE PRESSURE RELEASE VALVE BEGAN TO LET OUT SOME OF THE GAS FROM WITHIN.  THIS HAPPENED BY DESIGN.  WHEN THE TEMP OF THE CANISTER AND THE AIR WITHIN INCREASES, SO DOES THE PRESSURE, ENGAGING THE VALVE AND REDUCING THE CHANCE OF A DAMAGED EMPTY CONTAINER.  THE SHIPMENT WAS SENT ONTO THE DESTINATION.

PRODUCT WAS LOADED AT A HIGHER TEMPERATURE THAN NORMAL AND A SMALL QUANTITY SPILLED ON THE OUTER METAL SURFACE IN THE CRASH BOX SOLIDIFIED BEFORE LOADER SEALED TRAILER.  DURING TRANSIT, THE HOT PRODUCT IN THE INNER TANK WARMED THE OUTER SURFACE SUFFICIENTLY BY HEAT TRANSFER THROUGH THE METAL, THAT THE SOLIDIFIED MATERIAL ON THE CRASH BOX SURFACE FINALLY WAS LIQUIFIED ENOUGH TO BE PICKED UP BY THE WIND AND WAS BLOWN ONTO THE WINDSHIELD AND HOOD AND FENDERS OF ANOTHER TRACTOR TRAILER RIG.  WHEN OUR DRIVER CHECKED HIS TRAILER, THERE WAS NO MORE MATERIAL LOOSE, AND THERE WERE NO LEAKS.  THE CLEANING AND DAMAGE TO THE OTHER TRUCK WAS HANDLED THROUGH OUR INSURANCE COMPANY.  THE OTHER VEHICLE WAS DRIVABLE, AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  THERE WAS NO KNOWN PRODUCT REACHING ANY WATERWAYS.

column168: ILLINOIS CENTRAL CARMAN WHILE DOING AN INSPECTION ON AN INDUSTRY SWITCH MOVE REPORTED A LIQUID LEAKING FROM UNDER CAR DDEX 23014 ALONG THE CENTER SILL.  JEFFERSON PARISH FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE AND CHECKED THE PH OF THE LIQUID AND FOUND THAT IT WAS BETWEEN 6 AND 7.  DUPONT RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND DID AND INSPECTION OF THE RAIL CAR.  HOLES WERE DISCOVERED IN THE TANK JACKET JUST BELOW THE MANWAY AREA.  THIS WAS ALLOWING RAIN WATER BETWEEN THE JACKET AND THE TANK WHICH WAS WHAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  ADDITIONALLY, SEVERAL OF THE BLIND FLANGES WERE MISSING BOLTS.  THE FLANGES WERE LOOSE WHICH ALLOWED VAPORS TO ESCAPE FROM THE CAR.  DUPONT RESPONSE TEAM SECURED THE FLANGES WITH NEW BOLTS AND THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO DUPONT.

ON APRIL 28, 1999 A BPA TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS UNLOADING 7500 GALLON OF HIGH SULFUR #2 DIESEL AT TRI-SON CONCRETE IN BELLAIRE, OH.  PRIOR TO UNLOADING THE DRIVER FAILED TO OBTAIN A TANK CHART.  AS A RESULT OF NOT KNOWING  THE AMOUNT OF ROOM TO UNLOAD IN THE TANK, THE DRIVER SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS.  THE PRODUCT CAME OUT OF THE VENT PIPE AND MANAGEMENT FROM THE CORAOPOLIS TERMINAL RESPONDED TO THE SPILL ALONG WITH WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENT GROUP.  WEAVERTOWN CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE ONTO THE SOIL.  THE OHIO EPA WAS NOTIFIED.

column168: THIS PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING IN THE WAREHOUSE OF A FEDEX BUILDING. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS A FLASH BOTTLE CONTAINING A HOUSE-BREAKING AID FOR PETS WAS LEAKING.  HOWEVER, SOME OF THE CONTENTS APPEARED TO BE DANGEROUS GOODS AND THE PACKAGE HAD NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKING, LABELING, NOR WAS A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION SENT WITH THE PACKAGE BY THE SHIPPER.  THUS IT IS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  THERE WERE SEVERAL TYPES OF PET PRODUCTS IN THE PACKAGE INCLUDING 4 AEROSOL CANS (METAL).  THERE WERE TWO FLEE AND TICK REPELLENT AEROSOLS (7 OZ. EACH), ONE 14 OZ. AEROSOL OF OUTDOOR DOG AND CAT REPELLENT, AND ONE 7 1/2 OZ. PRO-GROOM CANINE COAT CONDITIONER.  THIS LAST ITEM DID SAY "FLAMMABLE" ON IT.  ALSO IN THE PACKAGE WAS SOME DOG SHAMPOO WHICH IS ASSUMED TO BE NON-HAZARDOUS.  MSDS'S WERE OBTAINED ON THE THREE AEROSOLS.  ON THE PRO- GROOM CANINE COAT CONDITIONER THE FLASH POINT LISTED ON THE MSDS IS 60 DEGREES FARENHEIT.  THIS IS BELIEVED TO BE "AEROSOLS FLAMMABLE".  THE OTHER TWO TYPES OF AEROSOLS ARE BELIEVED TO BE "AEROSOLS NON-FLAMMABLE".  FAA AGENT CAROL POLSEN WAS NOTIFIED.  FEDEX WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING THEIR INVESTIGATION OF THE PACKAGE.

THIS PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE A.M. SORT WHILE IN THE BUILDING.  THE PACKAGE WAS NOT DROPPED AT THE STATION TO THEIR KNOWLEDGE BUT HAD A DENT IN THE SIDE. THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM FOLLOWING THE SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION.

THE PACKAGE THEN PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.

I WAS CALLED TO A SPILL AT DOOR 23, UNLOAD.  I PUT ON MY PPE, BROUGHT THE SPILL CART, AND RESPONDED.  THE PACKAGE WAS ALREADY ON THE DOCK AND THE TRAILER WAS MOVED.  USING THE DECISION TREE, I USED THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUIDS.  I NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL TRAY AND BROUGHT TO PSC WHERE I PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.

THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN FRONT OF DOOR 102.  I RESPONDED TO THE LEAKING CORROSIVE PACKAGE WEARING PPE.  I USED THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET, NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLED MATERIAL USING SODIUM BICARBONATE AND THEN SOLIDIFIED THE WASTE.  I PUT THE WASTE INTO A DMP BAG AND PROCESSED THE WASTE THROUGH THE DMP.  THE PORTION THAT  WAS NOT DAMAGED WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

RESPONDED TO THE SPILL; PROCESSED VIA THE DMP PROGRAM; PROCESSED WITH ACTIVATED CARBON MATERIAL; PLACED IN BAG FOLLOWING UPS DISPOSAL PROCEDURES; I WORE THE PROPER PPE; DROPPED PACKAGE CAUSED LEAKAGE; HUB MANAGER SHOULD REVIEW PACKAGE HANDLING RULES.

RESPONDED TO BAY 16 UNLOAD FOR A LEAKING PKG.  DONNED PPE AND WENT TO TRAILER BLOCKED OFF AREA.  LOOKED AT DIAMOND LABEL AND SHIPPING PAPERS.  ALL SAID CORROSIVE.  TESTED WITH PH TAPE IT REGISTERED 12. REFERRED TO DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE GUIDE FOR CLEAN UP PROCEDURES.  REMOVED PACKAGE AND RELOCATED IT TO CAGE.  USING SODIUM BICARB I NEUTRALIZED LIQUID TO TEST PH 7 ABSORBED REMAINING LIQUID WITH CLAY BASED ABSORBENT AND PROCESSED THRU DMP PROCEDURES.

DRIVER ERROR-DRIVER HAD NOT CLOSED THE AIR INLET (BLOWDOWN) VALVE, AND LEFT LOADING RACK.  WHEN TRAILER WENT UPHILL TO PLANT GATE, PRODUCT DRIPPED FROM THE AIR INLET VALVE AND LEFT A TRAIL ON THE PLANT ROAD.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND PERSONNEL FROM GENERAL CHEMICAL CORP PERFORMED NEUTRALIZATION AND CLEANUP.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAYS.

UPON INSPECTING THE LOAD, DRIVER NOTICED SOME PRODUCT ON THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN IN THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER APPLIED SOME ABSORBING MATERIAL ON THE PRODUCT.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM AND THE CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO THE DRUM ALSO.  THE DRUM WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND TRANSPORTED ONTO THE FACILITY.
WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, FORKLIFT DRIVER HIT DRUM WITH FORKS. CAUSING A VERY SMALL PUNCTURE IN SIDE OF DRUM.  DRUM WAS PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM AND IS ON DOCK WAITING FOR DISPOSITION.

INCIDENT TOOK PLACE ON TERMINAL PROPERTY INSIDE TRAILER.  DOCK WORKER PUNCTURED 55 GALLON DRUM WHEN HE LOADED A PALLET UP AGAINST DRUM- DRUM WAS PUNCTURED APPROX 4" FROM BOTTOM OF DRUM.  WITH PROTECTIVE GEAR ON, WORKERS TURNED DRUM UPSIDE DOWN TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE.  APPROX 1/8 OF DRUM LEAKED OUT ON TRAILER FLOOR. AT THIS POINT CLEAN UP WAS PERFORMED.

A DRIVER PREPARING TO LOAD A PALLET OF DRUMS NOTICED A SMALL PUDDLE OF FLUID UNDER THE PALLET.  CLOSER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT A FIBER 55 GALLON DRUM HAS A CRACK THAT ALLOWED FOUR OUNCES OF WASTE TO LEAK ONTO THE CONCRETE FLOOR.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVER PACKED AND SPILLED WASTE WAS ABSORBED AND PROCESSED.  THIS SPILL GENERATED ONE POUND OF WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD, DENTON, TEXAS FOR TREATMENT/DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVE WAS BRIEFED TO LOOK FOR SLOW LEAKS PRIOR TO WAREHOUSING DRUMS.

a warehouseman moving drums with a forklift in temporary storage dropped a 55 gallon drum onto a concrete floor.  when the drum struck the floor top cracked releasing six gallons of waste.  the warehouseman overpacked the leaking drum and absorbed the spilled material.  this spill created sixty pounds of waste that was transported, along with the original waste, to the safety-kleen facility at 5756 alba st, los angles, ca for treatment/disposal. the warehouseman was counseled to use more care when moving drums with the forklift.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: AT ABOUT 8:30 AM ON THURSDAY,  APRIL 22, 1999, HARCROS CHEMICALS INC HAD A SPILL OF ABOUT 260 GALLONS (ABOUT 4,000 POUNDS) OF 93% SULFURIC ACID.  THE MATERIAL SPILLED FROM A 275 GALLON INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINER (IBC) THAT FELL OFF A IN-PLANT CART WHILE BEING TRANSPORTED FROM THE CONTAINER FILLING AREA TO THE MAIN WAREHOUSE.  THE TOP OF THE IBC SPLIT OPEN SPILLING ESSENTIALLY THE ENTIRE CONTENTS ONTO CONCRETE, AN ADJACENT GRASSY AREA, AND INTO A PLANT DITCH. THE SPILL AREA WAS IMMEDIATELY SECURED AND TRAINED HARCROS RESPONDERS STARTED SPREADING SODA ASH AND LIME ON THE SPILL SITE LESS THAN ONE HOUR AFTER THE INCIDENT BEGAN. BECAUSE OF IMMINENT RAINFALL, WE SPREAD AN EXCESS OF ALKALINE MATERIAL ON THE SPILL AND ALONG THE DITCH DRAINING THE AREA.  BEFORE WE COULD PROPERLY MIX IN AND NEUTRALIZE ALL THE ACID, HEAVY RAINFALL BEGAN.  PH SAMPLES OF WATER IN THE PLANT DITCH SYSTEM AND ALONG SPEAKER ROAD SHOWED NO ACIDIC MATERIAL IN THE WATER. ABOUT 3-1/2 INCHES ON RAIN FELL THAT AFTERNOON. THERE WAS MORE RAIN ON FRIDAY, 4/23 AND OVER THE WEEKEND SO REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES DID NOT CONTINUE UNTIL MONDAY, 4/26.  WE REMOVED MOST OF THE EXCESS ALKALINE MATERIAL FROM THE DITCH AND STARTED MIXING THE MORE CONTAMINATED SOIL.  AS OF LATE THIS AFTERNOON, THE PH OF MOST AREAS, INCLUDING THE SOIL AT THE BOTTOM OF THE DITCH, WAS NEUTRAL OR SLIGHTLY ALKALINE.  ONE HOT SPOT STILL HAD A PH OF 2 TO 3.  WE WILL CONTINUE TO MIX AND ADD NEUTRALIZING MATERIAL UNTIL WE GET THE PH OF ALL AREAS CLOSER TO NEURAL.  OTHER THAN SOME DEAD GRASS IN THE  IMMEDIATE AREA OF THE SPILL, THERE IS NO APPARENT ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE THE CAUSE OF THE IBC FALLING WAS PROBABLY DUE TO A BAD WHEEL ON THE CART. THE BAD WHEEL CAUSED VIBRATIONS WHICH PROBABLY SLOWLY SHIFTED THE IBC TO ONE SIDE UNTIL IT FELL OVER LANDING ON ITS TOP EDGE.  TO HELP PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN, WE ARE INCREASING OUR PREVENTIVE MAINTENANCE ON THESE  CARTS.  ALSO, WE ARE CONSIDERING WELDING SUPPORTS BARS ON EACH CART OR USING SOME OTHER METHOD TO PREVENT THE LOAD SHIFTING WHEN THERE IS EXCESS VIBRATION.

THIS LETTER IS A WRITTEN FOLLOW-UP REPORT TO OUR PHONE NOTIFICATION REGARDING THE ABOVE REFERENCED INCIDENT WHICH WAS REPORTED ON APRIL 7, 1999. THE INCIDENT INVOLVED A SPILL OF A STEPAN PRODUCT KNOW AS BIO-SOFT S-126 CONTAINING DODECYLBENZENE SULFONIC ACID (DBSA) (AS#27176-87-0) WHICH IS A CERCLA LISTED SUBSTANCE, BUT NOT AN EXTREMELY HAZARDOUS LISTED SUBSTANCE.  THE AMOUNT OF DBSA SPILLED WAS APPROXIMATELY 2500 POUNDS.  THE MATERIAL IS A THICK DARK COLORED "MOLASSES" TYPE SURFACTANT PRODUCT WITH NEGLIGIBLE VIOTALILITY.  THIS MATERIAL IS NOT A RCRA WASTE AND HAZARDOUS BASED ON PH.  THE MSDS IS ATTACHED FOR BIO-SOFT S-126. THE SPILL OCCURRED LATE ON THE EVENING OF APRIL 7, 1999.  THE SPILL OCCURRED WHEN THE OPERATOR HELPER UPON RE-CHECKING THE TANK CAR, DISCOVERED IT WAS OVERFLOWING.  THE OPERATOR HELPER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE LOADING PUMP.  UPON CHECKING THE TANK LEVEL GAUGE, IT WAS DISCOVERED THE MEASURING GAUGE HAD MALFUNCTIONED AND AS A RESULT, MORE MATERIAL HAD BEEN PUMPED OUT THAN THE OPERATOR HAD ESTIMATED 30 MINUTES PRIOR. IMMEDIATE RESPONSE ACTIONS THAT NIGHT INCLUDED USE OF STEPAN PERSONNEL TO CONTAIN AND DIKE THE MATERIAL ON THE ROADWAY.  THE IMPACTED AREA WAS APPROXIMATELY 15 BY 50 FEET.  THIS AREA IS OWNED BY STEPAN AND IT IS ENTIRELY WITHIN THE STEPAN FACILITY. A SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS ON-SITE FIRST THING THE NEXT MORNING AND THEY RECOVERED AND DRUMMED THE SPILL MATERIAL WITH A VACUUM TRUCK. IMPACTED GRAVEL WAS NEUTRALIZED, EXCAVATED AND PLACED INTO A 20 YARD ROLL-OFF BOX.  IT WAS SHIPPED FOR DISPOSAL ON APRIL 16, 1999.  ALL IMPACTED GRAVEL WAS EXCAVATED TO A DEPTH OF 1-2 FEET WHICH WAS BELOW ANY DETECTABLE DISCOLORATION OR OTHER INDICATION OF IMPACT. THERE WERE NO KNOWN OR ANTICIPATED ACUTE CHRONIC HEALTH RISKS  ASSOCIATED WITH THIS SPILL.  STEPAN EMPLOYS ABOUT 400 PEOPLE AND THE SIC CODE FOR THE MANUFACTURING AREA IN WHICH THE RELEASE OCCURRED IS 2843. STEPAN BELIEVES THE INCIDENT HAS BEEN FULL REMEDIATED, HOWEVER, SHOULD THERE BE ANY FURTHER QUESTIONS CONCERNING THIS INCIDENT, PLEASE CONTACT ME AT (815) 774-5201.  STEPAN WILL BE SENDING A RESPONSE TO THE IEPA LETTER DATED APRIL 14, 1999, AND A COPY WILL BE SENT TO IEMA.

column168: ON 040399 AT APPROXIMATELY 530 AM MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, GEOFFREY REEDER, RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER STATING THE ABOVE CAR WAS LEAKING. A WITNESS REPORTED THE CAR WAS SLOSHING LIQUID WHEN IT WAS MOVED. THE CAR WAS SET OUT IN THE NORTH END STUB TRACK FOR REPAIR.  UPON ARRIVAL REEDER INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND SEAL 010408 ON THE MANWAY COVER.  THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK SEEMED TO BE AROUND THE HINGE. REEDER OPENED THE MANWAY AND FOUND THE GASKET WAS MISSING.  A NEW GASKET WAS FORMED FROM GORE TEX AND THE COVER REPLACED.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND THE CAR RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT WITHOUT DELAY.

H. L. BART REGIONAL MANGER CTS, WAS NOTIFIED BY DAVE GIANDOTTI, MTO FREEPORT/ANGELTON, OF A LEAKING TANKCAR IN TRACK 8 AT FREEPORT VELASCO YARD.  RESPONSE REVEALED THE LINER HAD FAILED ALLOWING THE ACID TO CONTACT THE TANK SHELL RESULTING IN THE ACID DETERIORATING THE TANK SHELL AT THE 4 O'CLOCK POSITION.  DOW CHEMICAL RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED ALONG WITH H L BART AND JOHN JACKSON OF THE UPPR.  A VETTERS BAG WAS STRAPPED TO THE CIRCUMFERENCE OF THE TANK SHELL AND INFLATED AGAINST THE HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE TANK THUS STOPPING THE LEAKAGE.  TANKCAR DOWX 6871 WAS TRANSFERRED IN THE DOW PLANT AT FREEPORT.  APPROXIMATELY 300 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED IN THE BALLAST BETWEEN TRACKS 7 & 8 ON THE SOUTH END OF THE YARD. MAGNESIUM CHLORIDE WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED PRODUCT.

EL PASO REPORTED TO RMCC UTLX 41121 WAS LEAKING VAPORS FROM TOP OF TANK CAR AND SOME MATERIAL DOWN SIDE OF CAR.  RMCC NOTIFIED MR. HERBY BART, REGIONAL MR. CTS AND MR. JOHN JACKSON - MGR CTS-EL PASO. MR. BART REQUESTED CHEMTREC NOTIFY SHIPPER.  MR. MARK WHITE, MUREX N.A. LTD (SHIPPER) STATED TO RMCC THAT HE WOULD SEND MAINTENANCE CREW TO REPAIR CAR.  MAINTENANCE CREW SECURED THE LOOSE BOLTS ON COVER AND THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED.

CLERK AT RIVER YARD REPORTED TANK CAR ACFX 83911 LEAKING FROM BOTTOM CAP.  SANDY AT RMCC NOTIFIED MGR CTS, JOHN JACKSON ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 1:20 PM, INSPECTED CAR, AND FOUND CAR ON BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE LEAKING APPROX 9 DROPS PER MINUTE.  MGR JACKSON REMOVED CAP AND REPLACED CUT GASKET.  LEAK WAS REPAIRED AT 245PM.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO INTERCHANGE WITH BNSF.  BROKEN SEAL # 48618 WAS REPLACED WITH SEAL #UPA 1558711 BY UPRR SPECIAL AGENT GLEN PALMORE.

column168: CSE DOCK WORKER CHRIS GODSEY WAS UNLOADING 55 GALLON DRUMS FROM TRAILER USING DRUM CLAMPS. HE PICKED UP DRUM TO FAST, CAUSING THE CLAMPS TO PUNCTURE THE SIDE OF THE DRUM. HE THEN CONTACTED INTERIM DOCK SUPERVISOR RAY ROBERTS, WHO THEN CONTAINED AND CLEANED THE SPILL.

I NOTICED A BAGGAGE CART WITH A BOX LABELED UN1070 AND WITH TWO (2) GREEN "NON-FLAMMABLE" LABELS AND TWO (2) YELLOW "OXIDIZER" LABELS. SINCE WE WERE FOGGED IN, I ASKED THE PASSENGER (KEVIN KINSELLA-BAROID) FOR THE HAZ-MAT SHIPPING PAPERS. HE ADVISED ME THAT THE BOX WAS MARKED WRONG. I ASKED HIM TO OPEN IT, WHICH HE DID. THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN THE BOX. THERE WAS ANOTHER BOX AND I ASKED HIM WHAT WA INSIDE. HE SAID JUST EQUIPMENT. IT WAS NOT MARKED AND TOOK HIS WORD FOR IT. WHEN RON AND I STARTED FUELING AND LOADING THE AIRCRAFT, MR. KINSELLA BROUGHT HIS EQUIPMENT OUT TO THE AIRCRAFT AND THE SMALLER, UNMARKED BOX FELL AND SOMETHING BROKE. I WAS IN THE AIRCRAFT CARGO DOOR AND HEARD THE BOX HIT THE CEMENT. RON WAS STANDING CLOSE TO HIM WHEN THE BOX FELL. MR.KINSELLA TOLD RON IT WAS WATER. (RON TOLD ME LATER THAT IT DIDN'T LOOK LIKE WATER, SO HE STRUCK HIS FINGER IN IT AND SMELLED. IT WAS SOME TYPE OF SOLVENT). I ASKED MR. KINSELLA WHY HE DID NOT TELL ME ABOUT THIS. HE SAID THAT HE DID. I WALKED OFF. MR. KINSELLA TOOK THE BOX TO THE CORNER OF THE WAITING ROOM AND WENT BACK TO BAROID TO GET SOME MORE OF THE LIQUID. I RETRIEVED THE BOX. IT CONTAINED A ONE (1) GALLON BROKEN, BROWN BOTTLE OF METHALENE CHLORIDE, UN1593 (PROPER SHIPPING NAME- DICHLOROMETHANE) I NOTIFIED PAT FEY, BPX-AMOCO DISPATCHED.

column168: FILE AS 3099, SHIPPER: THE VALSPAR CORPORATION, AWB# GSO5956439045 GMM, THIS WAS A 5800.1 REPORT ONLY. ON 4/23/99 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177. THE LOCATION OF THE ODOR WAS OUTSIDE OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT FACILITY IN A UNIT LOAD DEVICE. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, CHARLES JONES AND PAUL SCHMIDT RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY DISCOVERED 2 X 20 LITER OF PAINT MATERIAL PACKED IN METAL RECEPTACLES. THE OUTER RECEPTACLES WERE MARKED LABELED AND THE ATTACHMENTS WERE AS FOLLOWS: AN AIRWAY BILL WAS ON THE SHIPMENT, A VALSPAR MANUFACTURE LABEL, A FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL AND A CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY LABEL. THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME WAS PAINT, UN1263, PKG II. THE SPECIFICATION MARKINGS WERE UN1A1/Y2.4/300/USA M4121/S/98. UPON INSPECTION OF THE RECEPTACLE THEY FOUND SIGNS OF LEAKAGE AROUND THE CLOSURE. THIS WAS A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE THAT HAD AN INNER FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE THAT WAS FOUND TO BE BROKEN. THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNCE OF THE PRODUCT THAT LEAKED. ALSO FOUND WITH THE SHIPMENT WAS 2 MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS, A CERTIFIED PRODUCT DATA SHEET, A SHIPPING ORDER FORM AND THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS, ALL IN 1 BLISTER PACK ATTACHED TO THE ABOVE SHIPMENT. THE 2 PIECE SHIPMENT HAD 2 DIFFERENT AIRWAY BILL NUMBERS, THE NUMBER LISTED ABOVE IF OFF OF THE SHIPMENT THAT LEAKED. THE ONLY REASON FOUND FOR THE LEAKAGE WAS FAILURE OF INNER CLOSURE. THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO THE DESTINATION.

ON 4/22/99 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177. THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS IN OUR "C" BUILDING SORT FACILITY. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN, CHRISTOPHER CHAPPA RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL CHRISTOPHER DONNED HIS PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION. CHRISTOPHER DISCOVERED A WET FIBERBOARD BOX, AT THIS TIME THE BOX HAD A PH READING OF 0 - 1. THE OUTER BOX HAD THE FOLLOWING: MARKINGS AND LABELS, THE TOP OF THE BOX WAS MARKED DNR 1027, 29440, D-N7, VALE, VALE INDUSTRIES INC., 122 SIMONDS AVE DE KALB IL 60115. TO: GEORGETOWN STEEL CORP., 1219 FRONT ST. (PLANT NORTH GATE), GEORETOWN, SC 29440 PO# 09098-101. THE MANUFACTURE SEAL IS AS FOLLOWS: ODMAN CORP., CHICAGO, IL 65LBS GROSS WEIGHT. THERE WERE NO OTHER MARKINGS, LABELS OR ATTACHMENTS ON THE OUTER BOX TO INDICATE THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND: 2 EQUIPMENT TYPE BATTERY CHARGES, CHRISTOPHER CHAPPA STATED THAT 1 OF THE CHARGERS APPEARED TO HAVE ACID IN IT. THERE WAS ALSO 1 PLASTIC BOTTLE THAT APPEARED TO HAVE BATTERY ACID IN IT, WHICH LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES OF ACID. THE BOTTLE WAS LEAKING FROM A PUNCTURE HOLE ABOUT 1 INCH FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE BOTTLE, ON THE SIDE. THE PUNCTURE APPEARED TO BE FROM A BLADE ON ONE OF THE BATTERY CHARGERS. THE CHARGERS AND BATTERY ACID WERE PACKED WITH STYROFOAM PEANUTS. THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED DUE TO THE SPILL AND IS BEING HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

THIS PACKAGE WAS NOTICED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION. THE INNER PACKAGING AND PERSONAL ITEMS THAT WERE INSIDE THE BOX WERE SLIGHTLY AFFECTED. THE LEAKAGE PACKAGE WAS CALLED STAIN PRO, AND THEY WERE CONTACTED FOR A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET REGARDING THE PRODUCT. FLASH POINT ON THIS COMMODITY WAS 114 DEGREE FARENHEIGHT. BOB CLATTERBUCK WITH THE MSP/CASFO WAS NOTIFIED AND WAS TO INVESTIGATE THE INCIDENT. THE OUTER PACKAGING WAS NOT LABELED OR MARKED TO SUGGEST ANY DANGEROUS GOODS PRODUCT WAS INSIDE AND THERE WAS NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK FOR THIS SHIPMENT.

column168: DAVID SMITH, YARDMASTER TO REPORTED TO RMCC AT 12:07 AM THAT A CONTAINER WITH A WAYBILL MARKED "MIXED HAZARDOUS WAS DRIPPING NEAR TRACK 801 ON THE EAST SIDE OF ICTF. HE REPORTED THE CONTAINER WAS DRIPPING QUANTITIES FROM THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS TO THE SIDE AND ABSORBANTS WERE PLACED TO CATCH THE DRIP. DENNIS JOHNSON, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER AND CHRISTINE CHRISTMAS, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS WERE NOTIFIED AT 12:47 AM. CHRISTINE CHRISTMAS ARRIVED ONSITE WITH TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL (TEC). THE EXTERIOR OF THE UNIT WAS INSPECTED AND FIELD TESTING OF THE MATERIALS WAS CONDUCTED AND CONFIRMED THAT IT HAD THE CHARACTERISTICS OF AROMATIC EXTRACTS. THE DOORS OF THE CONTAINER WERE OPENED AND THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED. THE LOAD WAS NOT BLOCKED OR BRACED AND NOT COMPLELETY FULL. THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED SIGNIFICANTLY. THERE WERE APPROXIMATELY 40 DRUMS AND 12 5GAL CONTAINERS INSIDE. TEC CLOSED THE DOORS AND THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATION DOCK FOR REWORK. AT THE DOCK, TEC ENTERED THE CONTAINER TO INSPECT THE CARGO. THE OVERALL CONDITION OF THE LOAD WAS POOR. TEC REMOVED SOME OF THE LADING IN ORDER  TO FIND THE LEAKING CONTAINERS. A NUMBER OF  THE DRUMS AND PAILS WERE DAMAGED, AND TWO WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING. ONE DRUM OF ORANGE OIL WAS ON ITS SIDE AND HAD APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS. ONE PAIL OF LEMON ESSENCE WAS CRACKED AND LEAKING FROM A DENT IN ITS SIDE AND HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS. THE CONTAINERS WERE CLEANED, PATCHED AND OVERPACKED. THE CONTAINER WAS SECURED AND CLOSED IN ORDER FOR TEC TO RETURN THE NEXT MORNING TO FINISH SECURING THE CONTENTS. THEY LEFT THE SITE APPROXIMATELY 4:15 AM. TEC RETURNED THE NEXT DAY AT 9 AM AND COMPLETED SECURING THE CONTENTS. TEC STOOD DOWN TO AWAIT INSTRUCTION FROM SHIPPER AS TO THE DISPOSITION OF THE CARGO. AFTER RECIEVING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER, TEC RETURNED TO THE SITE ON APRIL 16TH TO RELOAD THE LADING IN THE CONTAINER. TEC WAS ADVISED BY SHIPPER THAT THE CARGO WOULD BE  DIVETED TO A LOCAL FACILITY FOR RECOUP RATHER THAN BEING SENT ON TO THE OVERSEAS DESTINATION . IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE INFORMATION, TEC RELOADED THE CONTAINER, AND BLOCKED AND BRACED IT FOR LOCAL OVER-THE-ROAD DELIVERY.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE ONE SPOT  CAR REPAIR SHOP, COLTON, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR. DEVELOPED THE ABOVE TANK CAR WAS BEING SWITCHED INTO THE RIP TRACK FOR REPAIRS WHEN MEMBERS OF THE CAR DEPARTMENT ABSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE REPAIR FACILITY, LOCATED THE CAR ON THE RIP  TRACK #077, AND NOTICED A SMALL PRODUCT TRAIL FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR, DRIPPING DOWN THE LEFT SIDE  OF THE CAR. INSPECTIONFOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE VACUUM BREAKER VALVE LOCATED INSIDE OF THE PROTECTIVE COVER FOR THE TOP LIQUID AND AIR VALVES. THE VACUUM BREAKER WAS REMOVED, INSPECTED, AND FOUND TO HAVE A DISTORED GASKET. SINCE A REPALCMENT GASKET WAS NOT AVAILABLE, THE VALVE WAS REPLACED WITH A 1 1/2 INCH PIPE PLUG TO SECURE AGAINST ANY ADDITIONAL RELEASE OF PRODUCT. CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, GREG GARHART, MANAGER, SAFETY & TRAINING, SOUTHWEST SOLVENTS CHEMICAL, HOUSTON, TEXAS, DEVELOPED THE CAR WAS SAFE TO MOVE IN THIS CONDITION ONCE THE MECHANICAL REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED BY THE CAR DEPARTMENT. MR. GARHART WOULD ARRANGE TO SHIP A REPLACEMENT VACUUM BREAKER VALVE TO THE CONSIGNEE LACATED IN EUGENE, OREGON, AND HAVE THEM INSTALL THE VALVE PRIOR TO OFF LOADING THE CAR. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT  THE ICTF, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIS. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED ICTF SECURITY AND WAS ADVISED SOMEONE HAD MADE AN  ANONYMOUS PHONE CALL TO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT REPORTING STRONG ODORS IN THE FACILITY, AND THAT THE LOS ANGELES CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD RESPONDED. AT THE TIME, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD THE ENTIRE FACILITY CLOSED DOWN. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF, AND MET WITH MEMBERS FROM THE LOS ANGELES CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT, LOS ANGELES CITY HAZ MAT, LOS ANGELES COUNTY HEALTH HAZ MAT, AND THE AIR QUALITY MANAGEMENT DISTRICT. THE SOURCE OF THE ODORS WAS FROM THE  ABOVE CONTAINER THAT WAS PACKED CURB SIDE ADJACENT TO THE CUSTOM'S DOCK. THIS CONTAINER HAD BEEN INSPECTED THE PREVIOUS DAY  ACCOUNT REPORTED OF ODORS, AND PHYSICAL SIGNS OF LEAKING PRODUCT WERE OBSERVED AT THAT TIME. AN EXTERIOR INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER WITH REPRESENTATIVES OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT NOTED NO PHYSICAL SIGN OF LEAKING PRODUCT. SINCE THERE WERE NO SIGNS OF LEAKAGE, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AGREED TO REOPENING THE INTERMODAL FACILITY, AND MOVING THE ISOLATION AREA TO WITHIN 100 FEET OF THE CONTAINERS LOCATION. AFTER SEVERAL HOURS OF PHONE CALLS TO VARIOUS REPRESENTATIVES OF THE VESSEL CARRIER, FRIEGHT FORWARDERS, WAREHOUSES, AND FREIGHT BROJKERS, CONTACT WAS MADE  WITH THE MANUFACTURER. MR LARRY HUFFINE, PHILLIPS CHEMICAL, PROVIDED THE PRODUCT AND TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE. ONCE THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ASSURED THROUGH MONITORING, THAT THERE WERE NO FLAMEABLE VAPORS BEING EMITTED FROM THE CONTAIBNER, THEY DEPARTED THE SITE. LOS ANGELES COUNTY HEALTH HAZ MAT WANTED THE SOURCE OF THE ODORS IDENTIFIED, WHICH REQUIRED THE CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER TO BE REMOVED AND INSPECTED. THE LADING CONSISTED OF 36 METAL 55 GALLON DRUMS, ALL OF WHICH WERE FLOOR STACKED. THEM BLOCKING AND BRACING USED TO SECURE THE DRUMS CONSISTED OF 2 EACH 4X4'S THAT WERE WEDEGED INTO THE CORRUGATED SIDE WALLS OF THE CONTAINER, 2 FEET FROM THE REAR DOORS. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED SECUREMENT PROTOCOL, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER AAR PAMPHLET 6C FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS VIA THE RAILROAD. column168: WHILE CONDUCTING AN OUTBOUND ROLL-BY INSPECTION OF TRAIN MNPEX-12 AT MAXWEEL, NE, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, FRANK LERCH NOTED THE SIDE OF TANK CAR. FLIX TO BE  MOIST, WITH WHAT APPEARED TO BE PRODUCT. MGR LERCH IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED TRAIN DISPATCHER AND HAD CAR SET OUT AT LEXING, NE MGR. LERCH INSPECTED THE CAR NOTING THE FOLLOWING; APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED OUT ONTO THE SIDER OF CAR WITH NO EXPOSURE TO THE GROUND OR WATERWAYS. SOURCE OF THE RELEASE WAS FROM THE FOLLOWING FILLINGS LOCATED UNDER THE COMBINATION HOUSING. APPROXIMATELY 1/3 OF THE GASKET UNDER THE 2 INCH BLIND FLANGE (AIR), WAS MISSING, REMAINING GASKET WAS DRY, BRITTLE, AND CRACKED. ADDITIONALLY, TWO OF THE FOUR 1 1/2 X 3/8 INCH BOLTS SECURING THE BLIND FLANGE WERE MISSING. THE WERE TWO GASKET NOTED UNDER THE 3 1/2 INCH BLIND FLANGE (LIQUID). APPROXIMATELY 1/4 OF THE BOTTOM GASKET WAS MISSING. REMAINING GASKETS WERE DRY, BRITTLE, AND CRACKED. THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WAS IN POOR CONDITION AND NOTED TO BE  FROZE IN THE OPEN POSITION . INSPECTION OF THE MANWAY GASKET REVEALED IT TO ALSO BE IN POOR CONDITION, CRACKED AND BRITTLE. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT ALTHOUGH IT'S CONDITION WAS POOR, THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT FROM THIS OPENING. AFTER IDENTIFTY THE ABOVE MENTIONED EXCEPTIONS, THE FOLLOWING CORRECTIVE ACTION WAS TAKEN BY MGR. LENCH. ALL GASKET SURFACES WERE CLEANED. A TEMPORARY "GASKET WAS FITTED TO THE 2 INCH BLIND FLANGE. THE FLANGE PLATE WAS THAN SECURED IN PLACE WITH FOUR BOLTS. MGR. OBTAINED BOLTS FROM A LOCAL VENDOR AND REPLACED THE TWO MISSING BOLTS A RUBBER GASKET, COMPATIBLE WITH THE PRODUCT WAS FITTED TO THE 3 1/2 INCH BLIND FLANGE , AND SECURED IN PLACE WITH FLANGE PLATE AND FOUR EXISTING BOLTS. THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WAS REMOVED AND THE OPENING PLUGGED WITH A 1 1/2 INCH STEEL PLUG. THE ORIGINAL MANWAY GASKET WAS REPLACED WITH A PRODUCT COMPATIBLE SLIP IN MANWAY NOZZLE GASKET. AFTER THE CAR WAS PROPERLY SECURED, MGR. LERCH NEUTRALIZED THE AFFECTED AREAS AND RELEASED THE CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FUTHER INCIDENT. THE CAR WAS TAGGED TO BE HOME SHOPPED AFTER BEING UNLOADED. ALL EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED ON THE TAG. column168: A CARDBOARD BOX CONTAINING A HIGH-POWERED PRESSURE WASHER WAS LOADED ON FLIGHT 307 FROM LONG BEACH TO SACRAMENTO.  WINAIR DOES NOT ACCEPT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FOR SHIPMENT.  DURING TRANSPORT, THE BOX MUST HAVE TIPPED OVER, CAUSING THE GASOLINE TO SPILL OUT, SOAKING INTO THE BOX AND ON THE BIN FLOOR.  AMERICA WEST RAMP AGENT MORGAN MCINTIRE DISCOVERED THE INCIDENT.  SHE NOTIFIED THE CAPTAIN OF THE BIN FLOOR.  MAINTENANCE AND SMF COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE CALLED TO INSPECT THE AIRCRAFT.  UPON THE FIRE DEPARTMENT'S APPROVAL, THE AIRCRAFT WAS CHECKED AND CLEARED TO LEAVE.  FAA INSPECTOR, PETE WILHELM, HAPPENED TO BE AT THE AIRPORT, SAW A LOT OF PEOPLE NEAR THE AIRCRAFT AND INQUIRED AS TO WHAT WAS GOING ON.  HE BEGAN TO FILE A REPORT TO REFER THE INCIDENT TO THE FAA DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST.

ODOR APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM THESE PACKAGES.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS THEY CONTAINED HELICOPTER PARTS (FUEL CONTROL UNIT) WHICH APPEARED TO BE LEAKING JET A FUEL.  AS THE PACKAGE DID NOT HAVE ANY DANGEROUS GOODS, MARKINGS, LABELING, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION, THEY ARE BELIEVED TO CONTAIN UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  FAA AGENT LARRY ONEIL WAS NOTIFIED.  FEDEX HELD THE SHIPMENT PENDING HIS INVESTIGATION.

ONE PACKAGE OF A 10 PIECE CONSIGNMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHILE IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE.  PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE COMPLETED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER.  THIS MSDS LISTED TOXICITY DATA WHICH INCLUDED AN ORAL RAT LD 50 NUMBER OF 105 MG/KG.  AS THE 1999 IATA TABLE 3.6A LISTS THIS AS MEETING THE DEFINITION OF A HAZARD CLASS 6.1 PACKING GROUP III, IT APPEARED TO BE DANGEROUS GOODS.  AS THE PACKAGE WAS NOT SENT WITH DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS, LABELING, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION, IT WAS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS, PROBABLY "TOXIC LIQUID, ORGANIC, NOS," 6.1 UN 3287.  FAA AGENT BOB CLATTERBUCK WAS NOTIFIED AND THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING HIS INVESTIGATION.  I NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THAT WE WERE HOLDING IT PENDING INVESTIGATION FOR UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  THEY CONTACTED THE MANUFACTURER WHO SAID THE COMMODITY WAS NOT IN ITS PURE FORM AND SENT A CORRECTED MSDS WITH A LETTER OF EXPLANATION.  ON THE NEW MSDS THEY DON'T LIST ANY LD 50 NUMBERS BUT IN THE LETTER THEY SAY THAT THERE IS ONLY 0.3% MIXTURE OF NICKEL CHLORIDE.  I FORWARDED THIS NEW PAPERWORK SUPPLIED BY THE MANUFACTURER TO FAA BOB CLATTERBUCK FOR HIS REVIEW.  HE AGREED THAT THIS MIXTURE WOULD NOT BE A DANGEROUS GOODS FOR TRANSPORTATION BASED ON THE NEW MSDS AND LETTER FROM THE MANUFACTURER AND WE WERE ABLE TO RELEASE THE SHIPMENT AND SEND IT THROUGH OUR SYSTEM.

column168: MR. GERRY HILLIARD, A CUSTOMER AT HUNTINGDON HOOKED HIS TRUCK TO AN ANHYDROUS NURSE TANK, PULLED ON THE SCALES, WEIGHED AND STARTED TO LEAVE THE PARKING LOT. THE SEA-LAND HOUSTON OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED BY EMAIL THAT THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN DAMAGED, AND WAS AT HATCH 6, BELOW DECK, CELL 04 ON THE VESSEL. THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED WITH 32 DRUMS OF PHOSPHORIC ACID, UN 1805, CLASS 8, 21962LBS AND 32 DRUMS, AND 21927LBS OF A NON-HAZARDOUS PRODUCT. THE CHIEF MATE WAS ABLE TO DETERMINE DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINER CONSISTED OF AN OPEN TEAR ON THE PORT SIDE TOWARDS THE FORWARD END OF THE BOX DUE TO BUCKLING OF THE SHELL STRUCTURE AND DEFORMATION OF THE FORWARD LIFTING FRAME. UPON RECEIPT OF NOTIFICATION THE SEA-LAND OFFICE AT HOUSTON, TX CONTACTED BOOTS AND COOTS EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AND PORT OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT TEAM ON 4/22/99 TO DISCUSS A TENTATIVE CLEAN-UP PLAN. BRETT BAILEY AND ALISA SHELTON OF BOOTS AND COOTS AND MIKE ODOR WITH PORT FIRE DEPARTMENT MET WITH SEA-LAND ON 4/22/99 AT 3:30 ABOUT THE CLEAN-UP RESPONSE AND THE TENTATIVE PLAN. LIEUTENANT BERLINER OF USCG REQUESTED A COPY OF MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET AND THE PROPOSED PLAN WAS APPROVED. AT THE REQUEST OF THE USCG STEVE HAMM OF BALL CONTACTED BRETT BAILEY AT 11:30 p.m. ON 4/23/99 REQUESTING A COPY OF THEIR HEALTH AND SAFETY PLAN. THE CAPTION OF THE HAWA11 CALLED AT 11:20 a.m. ON 4/23/99 TO ADVISE THAT THE CONTAINER APPEARED TO HAVE STOPPED LEAKING AND THE VESSEL HAD CLEANED UP MOST OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT. NO PRODUCT HAD GOTTEN INTO THE WATERWAY AND NO ONE WAS INJURED. THE VESSEL WAS UPDATED ABOUT THE PLANS FOR CLEANUP, UPON ARRIVAL AT HOUSTON.

column168: TANK CAR NCTX 20241, LOAD SULFURIC ACID, SPLASHED PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS AT CSXT'S YEOMAN YARD IN TAMPA, FL.  SWITHMAN, D. C. MCCARTNAY, WAS SPLASHED ON THE SHOULDER AND ARM.  HE WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS TREATED FOR FIRST AND SECOND DEGREE BURNS AND RELEASED.  THE CAR LOADER, MARTIN GAS CO. RESPONDED.  THEY INSPECTED THE CAR AND REPLACED A CRACKED MANWAY GASKET, MARTIN GAS ALSO CHECKED THE RUPTURE DISK AND FOUND IT WAS IN TACT.  THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED.  ON MONDAY 5/3 FL DOT HAZMAT INSPECTOR, JAMES ALFORD, INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE DISK HAD BEEN RUPTURED. CSXTS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SENIOR MANAGER, E.G. COOK CHECKED THE CAR AND REPLACED THE BLOWN 165 LB DISK WITH A LIKE RATED DISK.

column168: MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY RICHARD TUFTS WAS NOTIFIED BY RISK MANAGEMENT DISPATCHER AT 2144 HRS ON 04/19/99 THAT TANKCAR NATX25772 WAS EMITTING AN ODOR AT THE A&S RR YARD IN EAST ST.LOUIS, IL. MANAGER TUFTS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND INSPECTED THE RAILCAR FINDING THAT THE VAPOR/AIR VALVE WAS LOOSE AT ITS POINT OF INSPECTION INTO THE COVER PLATE 1 & 1/2 TURNS AND THE LIQUID VALVE PLUG WAS LOOSE 2 TURNS, HOWEVER WAS UNABLE TO DETERMINE ANY LEAKAGE FROM THAT LOCATION. THE VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE ALL CHECKED WITH SNOOP AND NO LEAKS WERE DETECTED. ALL LOOSE VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE SECURED. ONE MANWAY SWING BOLT WAS MINIMALLY LOOSE AND TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELY 1/2 TURN. MANAGER TUFTS FOUND UPON CLOSE INSPECTION THAT THE PACKING GLAND NUT LOCATED ON THE EXTERNAL SECONDARY BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE STEM WAS LOOSE AND A SLIGHT DRIP OF PRODUCT  WAS NOTED. MANAGER TUFTS SECURED THE NUT WHICH STOPPED THE SEEPAGE OF PRODUCT AT THIS LOCATION. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO DESTINATION AT 2335 HRS.

MYO TOM FELZ REPORTED TO MGR CHEM TRANS SAFETY LARRY WILDER THAT DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS, TANK CAU UTLX 201181 LOCATED ON TRACK 2 YARD Y WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT. UPON INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR MGR WILDER FOUND 4 MANWAY COVER BOLTS LOOSE THREE QUARTERS OF A TURN. MGR WILDER NOTED THERE WAS EVIDENCE OF A MINOR SPLASH ON THE SIDE OF THE TANK CAR NO PRODUCT ON THE GROUND, NO WATER WAYS OR DRAINS INVOLVED. MGR WILDER TIGHTEN ALL THE BOLTS ON THE MANWAY COVER AND CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

V. CAMPEUCHIOLLI WAS LOADING SKID INTO TRAILER WHEN HE MISJUDGE THE WIDTH OF THE SKID HE WAS LOADING.  IT STRUCK THE SIDE OF A BOX CONTAINING THE HAZMAT, WHICH TUNE THRU THE BOX AND CRUSHED ONE - ONE QUART BOTTLE OF M.E.K.  DSR WAS VERBALLY INSTRUCTED TO BE MORE CAREFUL WHEN LOADING SKIDS, AND MAKING SURE HAZMAT IS PROPERLY PROTECTED BEFORE LOADING SUBSEQUENT FREIGHT REAR IT.

THE PACKAGE DEVELOPED A CRACK ON THE SIDE OF BOTTLE DUE TO A PACKAGE FALLING ON TOP OF THE BOX. THE SPILL WAS LIMITED TO THE BOX AND SURROUNDING BOXES WITHIN THE PACKAGE CAR. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP USING PROPER PPE. NO EMPLOYEE EXPOSURE AND NO OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 16:05 ON SUNDAY, APRIL 4, 1999 OUR DRIVER MR. MYERS WAS DRIVING EAST ON DANA DR., HE WAS IN THE PROCESS OF TURNING LEFT ON TO CHURN CREEK DR. WHEN HE LOST CONTROL OF HIS TRAILER HE WAS PULLING. MR. MYERS SWITCHED HIS DELIVERIES AND UNLOADED HIS TRUCK PRIOR TO THIS LOAD AND DUE TO HIS SPEED AND GRAVITY, THE TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH 3204 GROSS GALLONS OF REGULAR GASOLINE. APPROXIMATELY 2000 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT WAS SPILLED AND THAT 800 GALLONS WAS RECOVERED OFF THE SURFACE OF THE STREET AND VACUUMED INTO A CROSS PETROLEUM TANKER TRUCK. THE REMAINING FUEL (1200 GALLONS) IN THE TANK WAS STINGERED IN TO A SEPARATE TANK ON THE SPARE CROSS PETROLEUM TANKER TRUCK BY BEN'S EQUIPMENT. THE FUEL TRAVELED SOUTH THROUGH A CITY STORM DRAIN, TRAVELED UNDER THE INTERSECTION AND PARKING LOTS OF THE NEARBY SHOPPING CENTER AND SURFACED AT A CULVERT. THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AT THAT AREA. BEN'S EQUIPMENT PROCEEDED TO VACUUM THE CULVERT WITH A VACUUM TRUCK AND WHEN THERE WAS NO VISIBLE PRODUCT THEY BEGAN FLUSHING THE STORM DRAINS CLEAR. THAT WATER WAS  CONTAINED AND VACUUMED. THE SITE WAS THEN LAID WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND MONITORED FOR SURFACING CONTAMINATION WHICH WAS NOT FOUND.
